'''Richard Herbert Alban''' (born January 17, 1929) is a former [[American football]] [[defensive back]] who played eight seasons for the [[Washington Redskins]] and [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] in the [[National Football League]].  Alban played [[college football]] at [[Northwestern University]], where he was used at [[Halfback (American football)|halfback]] and on [[defensive team|defense]].

Alban was drafted in the ninth round of the [[1952 NFL Draft]] and immediately started all 12 games for the Redskins his rookie year. His best season came in 1954, where he finished second in the league in [[interception]]s with nine and was selected to his only [[Pro Bowl]]. He was traded to the Steelers in 1956 and retired after the 1959 campaign.

== Early career ==
Alban was born in [[Hanover, Pennsylvania|Hanover]], [[Pennsylvania]] and attended La Porte High School in [[La Porte, Indiana]] where he graduated in 1948.<ref name="database">{{cite web|url=http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=ALBANDIC01|title=Dick Alban Statistics|work=Database Football|publisher=databaseSports.com.|accessdate=29 June 2013}}</ref><ref name="IndianaFootball">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiana-football.org/?q=node/11|title=ALBAN, RICHARD "DICK"|year=2009|publisher=Indiana Football Hall of Fame|accessdate=29 June 2013}}</ref> While in La Porte, Alban was named to the [[United Press International]] All-State football team in 1946 and 1947.<ref name="IndianaFootball"/> For his accomplishments, Alban was later inducted to the Indiana Football Hall of Fame in 1980.<ref name="IndianaFootball"/>

Alban played college football for Northwestern between 1949 and 1951. Alban joined a team that won the [[1949 Rose Bowl|Rose Bowl]] the previous year. He was injured at the start of his first season, however, Alban caught a 29 yard touchdown pass from [[quarterback]] Don Burson in a 38-20 victory against [[Colgate University]] on November 12.<ref name="colgate">{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=clBhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HHUNAAAAIBAJ&pg=5047,4739499&dq=dick+alban&hl=en|title=Cats Claw Colgate|date=November 19, 1949|work=The Dubuque Telegraph-Herald|publisher=Associated Press|page=19|accessdate=29 June 2013}}</ref>

He teamed up with [[Chuck Hren]] at halfback for the 1951 campaign. He rushed for 101 yards, including a 69 yard carry for a touchdown during an October 20 victory over Navy.<ref name="navygame">{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wmAbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=N04EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6381,2676834&dq=dick+alban&hl=en|title=Wildcats Long Runs Beat Navy|date=October 21, 1951|work=The Pittsburgh Press|publisher=United Press International|page=67|accessdate=29 June 2013}}</ref> He was selected to participate as a member of the East squad in the [[East<U+2013>West Shrine Game]] and as a member of the North squad at the [[Senior Bowl]] at years' end.<ref name="EastWest">{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=OMgwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=0jwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5353,5422247&dq=dick+alban&hl=en|title=Janowitz Late for East Drills|date=December 21, 1951|work=Ludington Daily News|publisher=Associated Press|page=7|accessdate=29 June 2013}}</ref><ref name="seniorbowl">{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=R-FQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=iCMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4499,5654782&dq=dick+alban&hl=en|title=Weatherall and Alban Added to North Roster|date=December 10, 1951|work=The Milwaukee Journal|publisher=Associated Press|page=23|accessdate=29 June 2013}}</ref>

== NFL career ==
In 1954, Alban had nine interceptions and was selected to his only [[Pro Bowl]].<ref name="stats">{{cite web|url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/A/AlbaDi00.htm|title=Dick Alban NFL Football Statistics|work=Pro Football Reference|publisher=Sports Reference LLC.|accessdate=29 June 2013}}</ref> On April 24, 1956, Alban was traded to the [[Detroit Lions]] for [[Dick Stanfel]]. The Lions then traded him to the Pittsburgh Steelers for offensive tackle [[Dick Modzelewski]].<ref name="Albantrade">{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_TAbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=8k0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=4786,3035448&dq=dick+alban&hl=en|title=Steelers Land Defensive Ace for 'Little Mo'|last=Livingston|first=Pat|date=April 25, 1956|work=The Pittsburgh Press|accessdate=29 June 2013}}</ref> In 1958, Alban had five interceptions for 25 yards and a forced fumble.<ref name="stats"/> Three of the interceptions came in a 24-16 win against his old team the Redskins on November 2.<ref name="threeinter">{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=DsdJAAAAIBAJ&sjid=8AoNAAAAIBAJ&pg=2850,529277&dq=dick+alban&hl=en|title=Pittsburgh Defeats the Redskins 24-16|last=Bradis|first=Joe|date=November 3, 1958|work=The Charleston News and Courier|publisher=Associated Press|page=4|accessdate=29 June 2013}}</ref> He finished fourth in the league with six interceptions in 1959.<ref name="stats"/> During an October 11 loss against the [[Philadelphia Eagles]], Alban returned an interception for 46 yards, the longest in his career.<ref name="stats"/><ref name="long">{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=LXxRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=8w8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=7371,1156090&dq=dick+alban&hl=en|title=Eagles Get Past Steelers|date=October 12, 1959|work=The Milwaukee Sentinel|publisher=United Press International|page=7|accessdate=29 June 2013}}</ref> He announced his retirement at the end of the year.

He finished his career with 30 interceptions in 96 games played.<ref name="stats"/>

== Later life ==
He later became an executive for an athletic clothing manufacturer in [[Memphis, Tennessee]].<ref name="IndianaFootball"/>

